{"title_page": "Agastya (film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{infobox film\n| name  = Agastya\n| image =Agastya_movie_poster.jpg\n| caption =Poster of ''Agastya''\n| director = K.Murali Krishna\n| producer = Akshya Kumar Parija\n| story = [[Prashanth Neel]]\n| based on = ''[[Ugramm]]''<br/>by Prashanth Neel\n| starring = [[Anubhav Mohanty]] <br/> [[Jhilik Bhattacharya]] <br/> [[Akash Dasnayak]]<br/>[[Mihir Das]]<br/> Manoj Mishra\n| music = [[Prem Anand]]\n| cinematography =\n| editing = Chandrasekhar Mishra\n| released = {{film date|2016|6|12|df=yes}}\n| runtime   =\n| country   = India\n| language  = [[Odia language|Odia]]\n| budget   = {{INR}}1.60 crore <!--Must cite a reliable published source with a reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb. no fan-sites.--> \n| gross   = {{INR}}2.40-3.20 crore <ref>[https://www.eodianews.in/2019/02/top-10-highest-collecting-odia-movies.html]</ref><!--Must cite a reliable published source with a reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb. no fan-sites.-->\n}}\n\n'''Agastya''' is a 2016 Indian [[Odia language|Odia]] [[Action film|action]] [[Thriller (genre)|thriller film]] directed by K. M Krishna and produced under Akshya Parija Productions. It was released on 12 June 2016 at Rajo festival.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}} It was one of the highest grossing Odia movies in 2016. [[Anubhav Mohanty]],<ref>{{cite web|title= Ollywood Filmography: Anubhav Mohanty (Complete List)|url =http://www.odiaportal.in/2016/01/Anubhab-Mohanty-Filmography.html|accessdate=}}</ref> [[Akash Dasnayak|Akash]], and Jhillik play lead roles.<ref>{{cite web|title= Upcoming movie of Ollywood Superstar Anubhav Mohanty|url =http://www.odiasantabanta.in/2015/07/agastya-odia-film-original-songs-video.html?m=1|accessdate=}}</ref> It is a remake of the 2014 [[Kannada]] [[Action film|action]] movie ''[[Ugramm]]''. The music was released by [[Amara Muzik]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Anubhav Mohanty]]\n* [[Jhilik Bhattacharya]]\n* [[Mihir Das]]\n* Monoj Mishra\n* Agastya Asthana\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Agastya\n| type       = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Prem Anand]]\n| cover      =\n| border     = \n| alt        = \n| released   = 12 June 2016\n| recorded   = 2016\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=18|s=14}}\n| language   = [[Odia language|Odia]]\n| label      =\n| director   = K.Murali Krishna\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nComplete soundtrack album was released on 27 September 2017.\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing    = \n| all_music      = [[Prem Anand]]\n| headline       = Track listing\n| extra_column   = Singer(s)\n| total_length   = {{Duration|m=18|s=14}}\n| title1         = Agastya(Title Track)\n| length1        = 4:50\n| extra1         = [[Ananya Nanda]] ,[[Humane Sagar]]<br/>Sricharana Mohanty<br/>Satyajeet Pradhan<br/>Sangram Mohanty<br/>Bishnu Mohan Kabi<br/>Asutosh Mohanty<br/>Tarikh Ajij<br/>Satyajeet Pradhan<br/>Sohini Mishra\n| lyrics1        = Subrata Swain\n| title2         = Dhire Dhire Bhala Pai Gali\n| length2        = 3:33\n| extra2         = [[Ananya Nanda]], [[Humane Sagar]]\n| lyrics2        = Subrata Swain\n| title3         = Rama Rama-e-Jhia Ta\n| length3        = 3:30\n| extra3         = Pragyan Hota<br/>Aryan Das<br/>Ashutosh Mohanty<br/>[[Humane Sagar]]\n| lyrics3        = Arun Mantri\n| title4         = Tipi Tipi Barsha Topa\n| length4        = 5:00\n| extra4         = [[Ananya Nanda]]\n| lyrics4        = Subrata Swain\n| title5         = Dhire Dhire (Sad Version)\n| length5        = 2:31\n| extra5         = [[Ananya Nanda]], [[Humane Sagar]]\n| lyrics5        = Subrata Swain\n}}\n\n== Satellite rights ==\n[[Zee Sarthak|Sarthak tv]] purchased the film's satellite rights for {{INR}}40 Lakhs, which was a record amount for an [[Cinema of Odisha|Ollywood]] film.<ref>https://increadibleorissa.com/odia-film-agastya-tv-rights-record-ollywood/amp/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|tt5889478}}\n*[http://www.odiaportal.in/2016/03/Agastya-Odia-Action-Movie-of-Anubhab-Mohanty.html Ollywood: New Odia Action Movie *AGASTYA* of Anubhab Mohanty]\n\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Indian action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Odia remakes of Kannada films]]\n[[Category:2010s Odia-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n\n\n{{2010s-action-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{infobox film\n| name  = Agastya\n| image =Agastya_movie_poster.jpg\n| caption =Poster of ''Agastya''\n| director = K.Murali Krishna\n| producer = Akshya Kumar Parija\n| story = [[Prashanth Neel]]\n| based on = ''[[Ugramm]]''<br/>by Prashanth Neel\n| starring = [[Anubhav Mohanty]] <br/> [[Jhilik Bhattacharya]] <br/> [[Akash Dasnayak]]<br/>[[Mihir Das]]<br/> Manoj Mishra\n| music = [[Prem Anand]]\n| cinematography =\n| editing = Chandrasekhar Mishra\n| released = {{film date|2016|6|12|df=yes}}\n| runtime   =\n| country   = India\n| language  = [[Odia language|Odia]]\n| budget   = {{INR}}1.60 crore <!--Must cite a reliable published source with a reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb. no fan-sites.--> \n| gross   = {{INR}}2.40-3.20 crore <ref>[https://www.eodianews.in/2019/02/top-10-highest-collecting-odia-movies.html]</ref><!--Must cite a reliable published source with a reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb. no fan-sites.-->\n}}\n\n'''Agastya''' is a 2016 Indian [[Odia language|Odia]] [[Action film|action]] [[Thriller(genre)|thriller film]] directed by K. M Krishna and produced under Akshya Parija Productions. It was released on 12 June 2016 at Rajo festival.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}} It was one of the highest grossing Odia movies in 2016. [[Anubhav Mohanty]],<ref>{{cite web|title= Ollywood Filmography: Anubhav Mohanty (Complete List)|url =http://www.odiaportal.in/2016/01/Anubhab-Mohanty-Filmography.html|accessdate=}}</ref> [[Akash Dasnayak|Akash]], and Jhillik play lead roles.<ref>{{cite web|title= Upcoming movie of Ollywood Superstar Anubhav Mohanty|url =http://www.odiasantabanta.in/2015/07/agastya-odia-film-original-songs-video.html?m=1|accessdate=}}</ref> It is a remake of the 2014 [[Kannada]] [[Action film|action]] movie ''[[Ugramm]]''. The music was released by [[Amara Muzik]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Anubhav Mohanty]]\n* [[Jhilik Bhattacharya]]\n* [[Mihir Das]]\n* Monoj Mishra\n* Agastya Asthana\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Agastya\n| type       = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Prem Anand]]\n| cover      =\n| border     = \n| alt        = \n| released   = 12 June 2016\n| recorded   = 2016\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=18|s=14}}\n| language   = [[Odia language|Odia]]\n| label      =\n| director   = K.Murali Krishna\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nComplete soundtrack album was released on 27 September 2017.\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing    = \n| all_music      = [[Prem Anand]]\n| headline       = Track listing\n| extra_column   = Singer(s)\n| total_length   = {{Duration|m=18|s=14}}\n| title1         = Agastya(Title Track)\n| length1        = 4:50\n| extra1         = [[Ananya Nanda]] ,[[Humane Sagar]]<br/>Sricharana Mohanty<br/>Satyajeet Pradhan<br/>Sangram Mohanty<br/>Bishnu Mohan Kabi<br/>Asutosh Mohanty<br/>Tarikh Ajij<br/>Satyajeet Pradhan<br/>Sohini Mishra\n| lyrics1        = Subrata Swain\n| title2         = Dhire Dhire Bhala Pai Gali\n| length2        = 3:33\n| extra2         = [[Ananya Nanda]], [[Humane Sagar]]\n| lyrics2        = Subrata Swain\n| title3         = Rama Rama-e-Jhia Ta\n| length3        = 3:30\n| extra3         = Pragyan Hota<br/>Aryan Das<br/>Ashutosh Mohanty<br/>[[Humane Sagar]]\n| lyrics3        = Arun Mantri\n| title4         = Tipi Tipi Barsha Topa\n| length4        = 5:00\n| extra4         = [[Ananya Nanda]]\n| lyrics4        = Subrata Swain\n| title5         = Dhire Dhire (Sad Version)\n| length5        = 2:31\n| extra5         = [[Ananya Nanda]], [[Humane Sagar]]\n| lyrics5        = Subrata Swain\n}}\n\n== Satellite rights ==\n[[Zee Sarthak|Sarthak tv]] purchased the film's satellite rights for {{INR}}40 Lakhs, which was a record amount for an [[Cinema of Odisha|Ollywood]] film.<ref>https://increadibleorissa.com/odia-film-agastya-tv-rights-record-ollywood/amp/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|tt5889478}}\n*[http://www.odiaportal.in/2016/03/Agastya-Odia-Action-Movie-of-Anubhab-Mohanty.html Ollywood: New Odia Action Movie *AGASTYA* of Anubhab Mohanty]\n\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Indian action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Odia remakes of Kannada films]]\n[[Category:2010s Odia-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n\n\n{{2010s-action-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Genericusername57", "label": "safe", "comment": "space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agastya_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Winter Sonata", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Winter Sonata\n| image              = Winter Sonata (TV series).jpg\n| caption            = Promotional poster\n| show_name_2        = Winter Love Story<br />Winter Love Song<br />Winter Ballad<br />Endless Love: Winter Sonata\n| genre              = [[Romance film|Romance]]<br />[[Melodrama]]\n| camera             = [[Multi-camera]]\n| picture_format     = [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]] ([[480i]] [[4:3]])<br/>[[PAL]] ([[576i]] 4:3)<br/>[[DVB-T]] ([[UHF television broadcasting|UHF]])\n| audio_format       = [[Dolby Digital|Dolby Digital 5.1]]<br />[[Datasat|Datasat Digital 5.1]]<br/>[[Sony Dynamic Digital Sound|Sony Digital 5.1]]\n| runtime            = 60 minutes<br />Mondays and Tuesdays at 21:55 ([[Korean Standard Time|KST]])\n| location           = [[Seoul]], [[Namiseom]]\n| producer           = [[Lee Hyung-min]]\n| developer          =\n| executive_producer = Kim Jong-sik<br />Kim Hee-yeol\n| writer             = Kim Eun-hee<br />Yoon Eun-kyung<br />[[Oh Soo-yeon]]\n| director           = [[Yoon Seok-ho]]\n| starring           = [[Bae Yong-joon]]<br />[[Choi Ji-woo]]\n| narrated           =\n| opentheme          = \"From the Beginning Until Now\" by Ryu<ref name=\"OST\">{{Cite AV media|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/winter-sonata-from-beginning-until-now-original-soundtrack/id178770195|title=Winter Sonata - From the Beginning Until Now Original Soundtrack (Korean Dorama) [\uaca8\uc6b8\uc5f0\uac00 - \ucc98\uc74c\ubd80\ud130 \uc9c0\uae08\uae4c\uc9c0] - Single|date=8 July 2006 |type=mp3|language=Korean|publisher=KBS Media}}</ref>\n| endtheme           = \"From the Beginning Until Now\" by Ryu<ref name=\"OST\" />\n| channel            = [[Korean Broadcasting System]]\n| company            = [[Pan Entertainment]]\n| country            = [[South Korea]]\n| language           = [[Korean language|Korean]]\n| network            = [[KBS2]]\n| first_run          = \n| first_aired        = {{start date|2002|1|14}}\n| last_aired         = {{end date|2002|3|19}}\n| related            = ''[[Autumn in My Heart]]''<br />''[[Summer Scent]]''<br />''[[Spring Waltz]]''\n| num_episodes       = 20\n| website            = http://www.kbs.co.kr/end_program/drama/winter/\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name|\n| title  = Winter Sonata\n| hangul = {{linktext|\uaca8\uc6b8|\uc5f0\uac00}}\n| hanja  = \uaca8\uc6b8{{linktext|\u6200|\u6b4c}}\n| rr     = Gyeoul yeonga\n| mr     = Ky\u014ful y\u014fn'ga\n}}\n'''''Winter Sonata''''' ({{ko-hhrm|\uaca8\uc6b8\uc5f0\uac00||Gyeoul Yeonga}}; also known as '''''Winter Love Story''''', '''''Winter Love Song''''' or '''''Winter Ballad''''') is a [[Korean drama|South Korean television drama series]] that aired on [[KBS2]] in 2002. Starring [[Bae Yong-joon]] and [[Choi Ji-woo]], it is the second part of the season-themed ''[[Endless Love (2000 TV series)|Endless Love series]]'' directed by [[Yoon Seok-ho]]. Filming primarily took place on the resort island of [[Namiseom]] and [[Seoul]].\n\nThe series is widely considered to be the [[Korean drama]] that launched the [[Korean Wave]] throughout Asia and worldwide.<ref name=\"remembering\"/> It has also been adapted into an [[anime]] series and a stage musical.\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe story begins when Joon-sang, the son of an eminent musician, moves to [[Chuncheon]], a rural city in South Korea. As an extraordinarily talented student, Joon-sang is welcomed by his fellow students as well as his teachers, but remains a quiet, introverted teenager. As a result of the belief that his biological father is dead, and serious disagreements with his mother, Joon-sang believes that no one truly loves him.\n\nOn his way to school one day, Joon-sang's classmate Yoo-jin, while sitting next to him on the bus, falls asleep on his shoulder. Joon-sang soon falls in love with Yoo-jin, who opens her innocent heart to him. Their love, however, is cut short after Joon-sang is badly injured in a car accident and, due to brain damage, suffers from [[amnesia]], unable to remember anything prior to his accident.\n\nJoon-sang's mother, yearning for Joon-sang's love and respect, has Joon-sang brainwashed by a psychologist, so that Joon-sang will not remember his painful childhood as an illegitimate child. As a result, Joon-sang's memories prior to the accident are erased. Joon-sang's mother decides to move to the [[United States]] with Joon-sang, where he can start a new life under the identity of Lee Min-hyung. His friends and teachers are told that Joon-sang is dead.\n\nTen years later, Min-hyung is an award-winning architect in the United States. He does not remember anything about his life in Korea. He is completely different, now an open-minded person who cares about other people. He returns to Korea and Yoo-jin sees him on the street, prompting her to put off her engagement to her childhood friend Sang-hyuk. Little does she know that Min-hyung is dating her friend and past rival Chae-rin. The story's plot thickens when Yoo-jin's interior design firm is awarded a project by Min-hyung's architectural firm, and has to work with Min-hyung. Yoo-jin sometimes wonders if he is her supposedly dead first love Joon-sang.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Bae Yong-joon]] as Kang Joon-sang / Lee Min-hyung\n*[[Choi Ji-woo]] as Jeong Yoo-jin\n*[[Park Yong-ha]] as Kim Sang-hyuk\n*[[Park Sol-mi]] as Oh Chae-rin\n*Lee Hye-eun as Kong Jin-sook\n*[[Ryu Seung-soo]] as Kwon Yong-gook\n*[[Kwon Hae-hyo]] as Kim [[Korean honorifics#Seonbae.2FHubae|seonbae]]\n*[[Song Ok-sook]] as Kang Mi-hee, Joon-sang's mother\n*[[Jung Dong-hwan]] as Kim Jin-woo, Sang-hyuk's father\n*[[Kim Hae-sook]] as Lee Yeong-hee, Yoo-jin's mother\n*Ha Ji-hye as Jeong Hee-jin, Yoo-jin's younger sister\n*Jung Won-joong as Park Jong-ho, \"Gargamel\"\n*[[Jang Hang-sun]] as Supervisor Min\n*Lee Hyo-chun as Park Ji-young, Sang-hyuk's mother\n*Park Hyun-sook as Lee Jeong-ah, Yoo-jin's colleague at Polaris\n*Son Jong-bum as Yoo-jin's colleague at Polaris\n*Yoo Yul as Radio broadcaster\n*Maeng Ho-rim as Dr. Ahn\n*Ha Jae-young as Jeong Hyeon-soo, Yoo-jin's father\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:Winter Sonata at Nami Island.jpg|thumb|250px|''Winter Sonata'' park at [[Namiseom]]]]\n''Winter Sonata'' is credited with causing the second wave of the [[Korean Wave]] and extending it to Japan and the Philippines.<ref name=\"winter sonata\"/> It improved the image of South Korea among the Japanese and set fashion trends throughout East Asia.<ref name=\"winter sonata\"/> The series was a commercial success; 330,000 DVDs and 1,200,000 copies of ''Winter Sonata'' [[novelization]]s were sold.<ref name=\"remembering\"/> The series yielded more than {{USD|27 billion}} when taking into account the profit it contributed to tourism.<ref name=\"winter sonata\">{{cite web|url=http://uniorb.com/ATREND/Japanwatch/wsdramafever.htm|title=Winter Sonata Fever|work=UNIORB|last=Lee|first=Diana|accessdate=2012-01-13|date=31 January 2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207142535/http://uniorb.com/ATREND/Japanwatch/wsdramafever.htm|archive-date=7 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The number of visitors to the island of [[Namiseom]] (where the series was shot) grew from 250,000 to over 650,000 after the series was aired.<ref name=\"winter sonata nami\">{{cite web|url=http://nwww.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20120110000723|title=K-drama fever impacts other industries|work=[[The Korea Herald]]|accessdate=2012-01-19|date=10 January 2012|last=Park|first=Min-young}}</ref> A statue of the main characters can also be found on the island at the spot where they first kissed.<ref name=\"winter sonata nami\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eng.gg.go.kr/2356|title=Nami Island immersed in another ''Winter Sonata''|date=21 December 2011|accessdate=2012-01-19|work=[[Gyeonggi-do]] English Blog|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120709195937/http://eng.gg.go.kr/2356|archivedate=9 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe series shot actor [[Bae Yong-joon]] into stardom in Asia, and he became especially popular among middle-aged Japanese women.<ref name=\"remembering\"/> When he first visited Japan in 2004, more than 3,000 women guarded by 350 policemen gathered at the airport to welcome him.<ref name=\"remembering\">{{cite web|url=http://nwww.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20111230000497|title=Remembering ''Winter Sonata'', the start of hallyu|date=30 December 2011|accessdate=2012-01-19|work=[[The Korea Herald]]|last=Lee|first=Claire}}</ref> [[Junichiro Koizumi]], the Japanese prime minister at the time, was quoted saying that Bae was more popular in Japan than himself.<ref name=\"remembering\"/>\n\nThe series was also aired in the Philippines in 2003 via [[GMA Network]]'s primetime block under the title ''Endless Love II: Winter Sonata'' and one of the highest rated shows at that time. As a result, it also brought the Korean Wave to the Philippines. Just like in Japan, [[Bae Yong-joon]] became popular among middle-aged women.\n\nThe series was a success in Asia and the Americas as well.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/dec/15/cowell-pop-k-pop|title=Bored by Cowell pop? Try K-pop|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2012-01-13|date=15 December 2011|last=Mukasa|first=Edwina}}</ref>\n\n==Ratings==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! width=100 | Date\n! width=100 | Episode\n! width=100 | Nationwide\n|- align=center\n| 2002-01-14 || 1 ||<span style=color:blue>'''16.3%'''</span>\n|- align=center\n| 2002-01-15 || 2 || 16.6%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-01-21 || 3 || 19.2%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-01-22 || 4 || 21.5%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-01-28 || 5 || 21.2%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-01-29 || 6 || 24.1%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-02-04 || 7 || 27.2%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-02-05 || 8 || 26.3%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-02-11 || 9 || 17.8%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-02-12 || 10|| 16.7%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-02-18 || 11|| 26.4%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-02-19 || 12|| 27.0%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-02-25 || 13|| 27.6%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-02-26 || 14||<span style=color:red> '''28.8%'''</span>\n|- align=center\n| 2002-03-04 || 15|| 26.4%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-03-05 || 16|| 26.4%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-03-11 || 17|| 23.3%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-03-12 || 18|| 22.4%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-03-18 || 19|| 23.7%\n|- align=center\n| 2002-03-19 || 20|| 24.5%\n|- align=\"center\"\n! colspan=2 | Average || 23.1%\n|}\n\n==Soundtrack==\n#\ucc98\uc74c\ubd80\ud130 \uc9c0\uae08\uae4c\uc9c0 ''Cheoeumbuteo Jigeumkkaji'' (From the Beginning Until Now) - performed by [[Ryu Si-won|Ryu (\ub958)]]\n#\"My Memory\" - performed by Ryu\n#\ucc98\uc74c ''Cheoeum'' (First Time)\n#\uadf8\ub300\ub9cc\uc774 ''Geudaeman'i'' (Only You) - performed by Ryu\n#\ucc98\uc74c\ubd80\ud130 \uc9c0\uae08\uae4c\uc9c0 ''Cheoeumbuteo Jigeumkkaji'' (From the Beginning Until Now) - instrumental version\n#\"My Memory\" - piano and violin version\n#\ubcf4\ub0bc \uc218 \uc5c6\ub294 \uc0ac\ub791 ''Ponael Su Eobsneun Sarang'' (The Love I Cannot Send) - performed by Seon (\uc120)\n#\uc2dc\uc791 ''Shijak'' (The Beginning)\n#\uadf8\ub300\ub9cc\uc774 ''Geudaeman'i'' (Only You) - piano and violin version\n#\"My Memory\" - piano version\n#\uc78a\uc9c0\ub9c8 ''Itjima'' (Don't Forget) - performed by Ryu\n#\uae30\uc5b5\uc18d\uc73c\ub85c ''Gieoksog'euro'' (Inside the Memories)\n#\uc5f0\uc778 ''Yeon'in'' (Lover) - performed by Ryu\n#\uc81c\ube44\uaf43 ''Jebikkoch'' (Violet) - performed by Ryu\n#\uadf8\ub300\ub9cc\uc774 ''Geudaeman'i'' (Only You) - piano version\n#\ucc98\uc74c ''Cheoeum'' (First Time) - piano version\n#\uc81c\ube44\uaf43 ''Jebikkoch'' (Violet) - instrumental\n#\"Love Hurts\" - [[Yiruma]] (Ep 1)\n#\"When The Love Falls\" - [[Yiruma]] (Ep 2)\n\nIn addition, \"Moment\" performed by Ryu and available on his album ''Ryu 2'' is included on some [[bootleg recording|bootleg version]]s of the ''Winter Sonata'' soundtrack.\n\n==International broadcast==\nThe drama first aired in Japan on [[NHK]] in 2004; it was [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]] in [[Japanese language|Japanese]] and edited into 60-minute episodes. The final episode (which aired on August 23, 2004) recorded ratings of 20.6% in [[Kant\u014d region|Kanto]], 22.5% in [[Nagoya]], and 23.8% in the [[Kansai region|Kansai]] regions. The series as a whole had an average viewership in the 14% to 15% range. Due to overwhelming demand from viewers to watch the series in its original format, it was re-aired on NHK's satellite channel BS2 unedited (in its original Korean audio, with Japanese [[subtitle (captioning)|subtitles]]), beginning December 20, 2004.<ref>{{cite web|title=Japanese Satellite Channel to Air ''Winter Sonata'' No-Cut|url=http://english.kbs.co.kr/hallyu/entertainment_news_view.html?No=1376|work=KBS Global|accessdate=2013-09-13|date=3 November 2004}}</ref>\n\nIt was the first Korean drama that ushered in the [[Korean Wave]] in Malaysia, when it aired in 2002 on [[TV3 (Malaysia)|TV3]] [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]] in [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin]] with [[Malay language|Malay]] [[subtitles]]. PMP Entertainment later released the drama in VCD and DVD format under the Bahasa title, ''Kisah Cinta Musim Salju'' (meaning \"Winter Love Story\"). A Malay [[cover version]] of the theme song was released with the title \"Sonata Musim Salju\" (meaning \"Winter's Sonata\").\n\nThe drama aired in [[Nepal]] on [[Kantipur Television Network]] in the mid-2000s dubbed in [[Nepali language|Nepali]]. The drama triggered the Korean Wave in the country.\n\nIn 2006, pan-[[Asian American]] network [[AZN Television]] bought the rights to air ''Winter Sonata'' in a 24-hour [[marathon (television)|marathon]] with other [[Korean drama]]s.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://english.ohmynews.com/articleview/article_view.asp?menu=c10400&no=311272&rel_no=1 | title='Winter Sonata' Spell Cast on One More - OhmyNews International}}</ref>\n\nIn Asia, the drama is available to stream via [[Iflix]] with English, Indonesian, Malay, Simplified Mandarin, Sinhalese, Vietnamese and Burmese subtitles.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://m.iflix.com/title/show/1813 |title = Iflix}}</ref>\n\n==Anime==\nAn [[anime]] adaptation of ''Winter Sonata'' premiered on Japan's [[SKY PerfecTV!]] on October 17, 2009, consisting of 26 episodes subtitled in Japanese. Directed by Ahn Jae-hoon and written by Kim Hyeong-wan, the program featured 23 members of the original Korean cast voicing the characters, including Bae and Choi who reprised their roles. The role of \"Sang-hyuk\", originally played by [[Park Yong-ha]], was voiced by singer Kang Yo-hwan and \"Chae-rin\" was dubbed by newcomer Lee Se-na in place of [[Park Sol-mi]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Hyo-won|title=Bae, Choi to Voice Winter Sonata Cartoon|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/special/2008/05/178_25074.html|work=[[The Korea Times]]|date=30 May 2008|accessdate=2012-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Choi|first=Ji-eun|title=A reunion in 7 years: Yonsama and Jiwoohime|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2009092918564427201|work=10Asia|date=29 September 2009|accessdate=2012-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\"Yonsama\" greeted by fans and white handkerchiefs|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2009093011263243101|website=10Asia|accessdate=2014-11-21|date=30 September 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kim|first=Lynn|title=Bae Yong-joon, Choi Ji-woo reunite for ''Winter Sonata'' anime|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010020212531420351|work=10Asia|date=2 February 2010|accessdate=2012-01-19}}</ref> During October 2011, [[Animax Asia]] aired the anime in Korean audio and English subtitles across [[South Asia|South]] and [[Southeast Asia]]. In 2019, Allen's Television Network revived the anime with Tagalog Subtitles in the Philippines. Allen Ca\u00f1ada revived the Theme song of Di Ko Na Kaya By Faith Cuneta.\n\n===Voice cast===\n====Korean version====\n*[[Bae Yong-joon]] as Kang Joon-sang / Lee Min-hyung\n*[[Choi Ji-woo]] as Jeong Yoo-jin\n*[[Kang Yo-hwan]] as Kim Sang-hyuk\n*[[Lee Se-na]] as Oh Chae-rin\n*[[Ryu Seung-soo]] as Kwon Yong-gook\n*Seon Jeon-hui as Kong Jin-sook, Catalina and Marianne\n*Bae Han-seon as Kim Jin-woo (Sang-hyuk's father)\n*So Hye-jyeon as Kang Mi-hee (Joon-sang's mother) and Anne\n*Yoon So-ra as Kim Yeong-hee (Yoo-jin's mother) and Mother superior\n*[[Lee Young-yoo]] as Jeong Hee-jin (Yoo-jin's younger sister)\n*Lee Jang-won as Park Jong-ho (teacher)\n*Choi Seon-woo as Park Ji-young (Sang-hyuk's mother)\n*Min-ji as Lee Jeong-ah\n*Park Yeong-jae as Hang Seung-ryong and DJ (Sang-hyuk's colleague)\n*Kim Chang as Kim Hyo-sook (Min-hyung's seonbae) and Jeong Hyeon-soo (Yoo-jin's father)\n*Kim Gyu-sik as Dr. Ahn\n*Seo-yeong as Jane\n*Cho Gyun-joon as Manager Kim (Mi-hee's manager)\n*Im Chae-hong as Claude\n*Nam Do-hyeong as Louis\n*Hong Seong-min as Chang\n*Kim In-jeong as Manufacturing manager\n\n====Japanese version====\n*[[Masato Hagiwara]] as Kang Joon-sang / Lee Min-hyung\n*[[Misato Tanaka]] as Jeong Yoo-jin\n*[[Kazuma Horie]] as Kim Sang-hyuk\n*[[Sayaka Kinoshita]] as Oh Chae-rin\n*[[Fuminori Komatsu]] as Kwon Yong-gook\n*[[Makoto Tsumura]] as Kong Jin-sook\n*Mitsuru Takakuwa as Kim Jin-woo, Sang-hyuk's father\n*Chika Mizuno as Kang Mi-hee, Joon-sang's mother\n*Kaoru Katakai as Kim Yeong-hee, Yoo-jin's mother\n*Michiko Komatsu as Jeong Hee-jin, Yoo-jin's younger sister\n*[[Binbin Takaoka]] as Park Jong-ho, teacher\n*Kikue Umimoto as Park Ji-young, Sang-hyuk's mother\n*Tatsuya Kamijo as Radio DJ\n*Aki Yasunaga as Lee Jeong-ah\n*Seiro Ogino as Kim Hyo-sook, Min-hyung's seonbae\n*Yasuhiro Mamiya as Dr. Ahn\n*Kumi Tanaka as Jane\n*Katsunori Kobayashi as Manager Kim, Mi-hee's manager\n*Kenji Sugimura as Claude\n*Ryo Agawa as Anne\n*Yuto Suzuki as Louis\n*Masanori Machida as Chang\n*Koki Yamada as Manufacturing manager\n*Kanako Hirano as Catalina.\n*[[Sayuri Sadaoka]] as Mother superior\n*Rinko Hayashi as Marianne\n*Keiichi Nakagawa as Jeong Hyeon-soo, Yoo-jin's father\n\n===Episode list===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=100 |Episode\n! width=100 |Date\n! width=300 |Title\n|- align=center\n| 0\n|\n|\"Prologue\" \n|- align=center\n| 1\n|2009-10-17\n|\"Black and White Photo\" \n|- align=center\n| 2\n|2009-10-24\n|\"Kingdom of Shadows\"\n|- align=center\n| 3\n|2009-10-31\n|\"First Time\"\n|- align=center\n| 4\n|2009-11-07\n|\"The Promise That Couldn't Be Kept\"\n|- align=center\n| 5\n|2009-11-14\n|\"Was Seeing You Just A Dream?\"\n|- align=center\n| 6\n|2009-11-21\n|\"The Woman Who Can't Forget Her First Love\"\n|- align=center\n| 7\n|2009-11-28\n|\"The Man Who Can't Remember Her\"\n|- align=center\n| 8\n|2009-12-05\n|\"Lie\"\n|- align=center\n| 9\n|2009-12-12\n|\"Me, Inside the Forgotten Time\"\n|- align=center\n| 10\n|2009-12-19\n|\"Me, Inside the Forgotten Time Part 2\"\n|- align=center\n| 11\n|2009-12-26\n|\"When First Love Call On Me Again\"\n|- align=center\n| 12\n|2010-01-09\n|\"A Love That's Waited Ten Years\"\n|- align=center\n| 13\n|2010-01-16\n|\"An Empty Name\"\n|- align=center\n| 14\n|2010-01-23\n|\"Polaris\"\n|- align=center\n| 15\n|2010-01-30\n|\"The Last Fragment of Memory\"\n|- align=center\n| 16\n|2010-02-13\n|\"The Last Fragment of Memory Part 2\"\n|- align=center\n| 17\n|2010-02-20\n|\"Our First and Our Last Ocean\"\n|- align=center\n| 18\n|2010-02-27\n|\"Everything Disappears as Winter Fades Away\"\n|- align=center\n| 19\n|2010-03-06\n|\"As Tears Go By\"\n|- align=center\n| 20\n|2010-03-13\n|\"The Impossible House\"\n|- align=center\n| 21\n|2010-03-20\n|\"The Traveler's Heart, Renewed\"\n|- align=center\n| 22\n|2010-03-27\n|\"First Love\"\n|- align=center\n| 23\n|2010-04-10\n|\"First Love Part 2\"\n|- align=center\n| 24\n|2010-04-17\n|\"A Winter of Shadow Pale\"\n|- align=center\n| 25\n|2010-04-24\n|\"From the Beginning Until Now\"\n|- align=center\n| 26\n|2010-05-01\n|\"Hidden Track - Eternal Love\"\n|}\n\n===Soundtrack===\n====Version 1====\n#\u6700\u521d\u304b\u3089\u4eca\u307e\u3067 Saisho kara Imamade